   (Message) The failure is not a crash. The interpreter exits normally, but
   `tests/string.be` fails because the string formatting implementation
   mishandles escaped percent signs.
   
   I traced execution under GDB with the working directory set to `/work` so
   `tests/string.be` could be loaded correctly. The earlier `find` assertions
   execute successfully. The first failing formatting case is:
   
   ```berry
   assert(s.format("%%") == "%")
   ```
   
   When `str_format()` is entered for this call:
   
   ```c
   top = be_top(vm)          // 1
   format = be_tostring(vm, 1) // "%%"
   index = 2
   ```
   
   There is only one Berry argument: the format string itself. That is correct,
   because `"%%"` should produce a literal percent and should not consume a
   formatting value.
   
   However, `str_format()` processes every percent sequence as if it requires an
   argument. The relevant code is:
   
   ```c
   p = get_mode(p + 1, mode);
   buf[0] = '\0';
   if (index > top) {
       be_raise(vm, "runtime_error", be_pushfstring(vm,
           "bad argument #%d to 'format': no value", index));
   }
   switch (*p) {
   ...
   ```
   
   For `"%%"`:
   
   1. `strchr(format, '%')` finds the first `%`.
   2. `pushstr(vm, format, p - format)` pushes the literal prefix, which is
   empty.
   3. `get_mode(p + 1, mode)` is called with the second `%`.
   4. `get_mode()` returns a pointer to that second `%`, so `*p == '%'`.
   5. Before `switch (*p)` can handle the conversion, the code checks `if (index
   > top)`.
   6. `index == 2`, `top == 1`, so the function raises `"bad argument #2 to
   'format': no value"`.
   
   That is wrong for `%%`: escaped percent is not a value-consuming conversion.
   The formatter should append `"%"` and should not require or consume an
   argument.
   
   There is a second related bug: `str_format()` has no `case '%'` in its
   `switch`. Even if the argument-count check were moved, `%%` would currently
   fall into the default error path:
   
   ```c
   default:
       be_raise(vm, "runtime_error", be_pushfstring(vm,
           "invalid option '%%%c' to 'format'", *p));
   ```
   
   So the immediate defect is that literal percent escapes are not supported by
   `str_format()`, even though the test expects C/Python-like formatting
   semantics where `"%%"` means a literal `%`.
   
   A correct local fix is to special-case `%` before checking for a value, and
   avoid incrementing `index` for that case.
   
   One minimal patch:
   
   ```diff
   diff --git a/src/be_strlib.c b/src/be_strlib.c
   index ... .. ...
   --- a/src/be_strlib.c
   +++ b/src/be_strlib.c
   @@ -511,8 +511,15 @@ static int str_format(bvm *vm)
                pushstr(vm, format, p - format);
                concat2(vm);
                p = get_mode(p + 1, mode);
                buf[0] = '\0';
   +
   +            /* "%%" is an escaped percent.  It does not consume an argument. */
   +            if (*p == '%') {
   +                pushstr(vm, "%", 1);
   +                concat2(vm);
   +                format = p + 1;
   +                continue;
   +            }
   +
                if (index > top) {
                    be_raise(vm, "runtime_error", be_pushfstring(vm,
                        "bad argument #%d to 'format': no value", index));
                }
                switch (*p) {
   ```
   
   With this behavior:
   
   ```berry
   s.format("%%")          // "%"
   s.format("%i%%", 12)    // "12%"
   s.format("%i%%%i", 12, 13) // "12%13"
   s.format("%s%%", "foo") // "foo%"
   ```
   
   The escaped percent no longer triggers the missing-argument check and does
   not increment the value index.
   
   ROOT CAUSE: `/work/src/be_strlib.c:515` in `str_format()`. The code checks
   `if (index > top)` for every `%` sequence before determining whether the
   sequence is `%%`. But `%%` is a literal percent escape and should not consume
   an argument. Because `index` starts at `2` and `top` is `1` for
   `s.format("%%")`, the formatter reports a missing second argument instead of
   returning `"%"`. The switch also lacks a `case '%'`, so escaped percent
   handling is absent entirely.
   
   LOCAL FIX: Add explicit handling for `%%` immediately after `get_mode()` and
   before the argument-count check, without incrementing `index`.
   
   ```diff
   @@ -511,8 +511,15 @@ static int str_format(bvm *vm)
                pushstr(vm, format, p - format);
                concat2(vm);
                p = get_mode(p + 1, mode);
                buf[0] = '\0';
   +            if (*p == '%') {
   +                pushstr(vm, "%", 1);
   +                concat2(vm);
   +                format = p + 1;
   +                continue;
   +            }
                if (index > top) {
                    be_raise(vm, "runtime_error", be_pushfstring(vm,
                        "bad argument #%d to 'format': no value", index));
                }
   ```
   
   GLOBAL FIX: Refactor `str_format()` so format parsing produces an explicit
   token type, e.g. `FORMAT_LITERAL_PERCENT`, `FORMAT_INT`, `FORMAT_REAL`,
   `FORMAT_STRING`, etc. Only value-consuming token types should perform
   argument-count checks or increment `index`. This prevents the parser from
   treating all `%` sequences uniformly and avoids future bugs where non-
   consuming directives, escaped characters, or invalid directives are mixed
   with value-consuming conversions.

